{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"59aa35ba-2285-4efa-a001-47412e821f32","content":"These are two **C# 15 breaking changes**:\n\n---\n\n**1. Dynamic short-circuit operators** — C# 15 no longer fully defers `&&`/`||` to the runtime when one operand is `dynamic`. The compiler now tries to resolve `operator true`/`operator false` at compile time on the static type (`IFilter`). Since `IFilter` lacks `operator &`, the compile-time partial binding fails.\n\n**Fix:** Cast to dynamic so everything is deferred to runtime:\n\n```csharp\nvar combined = (dynamic)left && right;\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518** — C# 15 requires a new well-known attribute type (`RefReadOnlyParameterAttribute` or similar) to emit metadata for `ref readonly` returns on synthesized delegate types. If your runtime libraries haven't been updated to .NET 11, that type doesn't exist yet.\n\n**Fix:** Ensure you're targeting `net11.0` and using the .NET 11 SDK/runtime libraries. If you can't upgrade the TFM yet, use a named method or local function instead of a lambda:\n\n```csharp\nstatic ref readonly int Fn() => ref value;\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c9d1139f-41da-4534-9552-3fea4d99c8d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both issues.\n\n**Issue 1: `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to short-circuit logical operators (`&&` / `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the compiler would allow `&&` with a dynamic operand even when the static type defined `operator true`/`operator false` on an interface. In C# 15, the compiler now correctly binds the user-defined `operator &` at compile time when possible, but the `operator true`/`operator false` on an interface with a `dynamic` operand causes issues.\n\n\nThe issue is that when using `&&` with a `dynamic` operand and an interface that defines `operator true`/`operator false` as static members, C# 15 now requires both the `operator &` and `operator true` to be available at compile time, but since one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler can't resolve this properly. to runtime when one operand is `dynamic` and the other has a static type with user-defined `operator true`/`operator false`. The compiler now tries to bind those operators at compile time, which fails when a `dynamic` operand is involved. I could fix this by casting the non-dynamic operand to `dynamic` as well, though the real issue might be more complex if `IFilter` and `CompositeFilter` both define these operators differently.\n\nLooking at the actual code, `IFilter` has static `operator true`/`operator false` methods, and C# 15 introduced a breaking change where the compiler resolves these operators at compile time instead of deferring to runtime when `dynamic` is involved. If the static type's operators can't be properly combined with the dynamic operand, it produces an error.\n\nThere's also a separate issue with `ref readonly` returns on lambdas, which is triggering a `CS0518` error about a predefined type not being defined. and `ref readonly` returns on lambdas and local functions now require `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RefReadOnlyParameterAttribute`, which causes CS0518 if the target framework doesn't include it. There's also a breaking change in C# 15 where short-circuit operators with `dynamic` now attempt compile-time binding of `operator true`/`operator false`, which can fail when the static type is an interface. Let me think through what the specific migration issues are here. operands to `dynamic` to work around the compile-time resolution issue. For Issue 2, the CS0518 error about missing metadata suggests the runtime libraries don't include the required attributes for lambda expressions with `ref readonly` returns in C# 15, so I need to verify the project is targeting .NET 11 with the correct SDK version or manually add the missing attribute type. The solution is to target `net11.0` or define the required attribute yourself. I should verify the exact breaking changes in .NET 11 preview 1 using the migration documentation rather than relying on assumptions about what changed.\n\nFor the first issue with short-circuit operators and `dynamic`, C# 15 changed how it resolves `operator true`/`operator false` when one operand is dynamic—it now tries to resolve these operators at compile-time on the non-dynamic operand's static type, which behaves differently when that type is an interface like `IFilter`.\n\nThe fix is to cast both operands to dynamic so the entire operation is handled at runtime.\n\nFor the second issue, `ref readonly` return lambdas require a synthesized delegate type that depends on a well-known attribute only available in .NET 11's runtime libraries, so you need to target `net11.0` and use the corresponding runtime libraries. now tries to evaluate `operator true(left)` at compile time since `left` has a known static type. But `IFilter` defines `operator true` as a non-virtual static method, which creates a mismatch when the right operand is dynamic—the `operator &` still needs dynamic dispatch, but `operator true` is now statically bound. The real problem is that `operator &` isn't defined on `IFilter` itself, only on `CompositeFilter`, so the compiler can't resolve it at compile time. The fix is to cast the left side to `dynamic` to defer the entire operation to runtime.\n\nFor the second issue with `ref readonly` in lambda parameters...\n\nthe CS0518 error suggests a missing well-known type that C# 15 requires for synthesized delegates with `ref readonly` returns. This typically means the runtime packages are out of sync or need updating to support the new language feature.","outputTokens":3370,"requestId":"6C36:DD840:E39815:10B698C:69FE937C"},"id":"288923fb-39cc-4c00-8d6a-c9b5628510f7","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:54:10.213Z","parentId":"b5e4d2ef-6a76-4520-a590-9e